<subSubSection pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1098,2023]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,345,1134,1159]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Description.</emphasis>
Test thin, flexible, contour circular (TD = 
<quantity box="[849,956,1134,1159]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.74" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="mm" value="67.4">67.4 mm</quantity>
). Preserved test becomes totally flattened (
<figureCitation box="[159,287,1170,1195]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1087,1109]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 4. Morphological characters of Phormosoma placenta (EqMN2341). (A) Aboral view. (B) Detail of apical system; (C) Oral view; (D) Peristome; (E) Ambulacral plates; (F) Interambulacral plates; (G) Valve of tridentate pedicellariae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612572/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 4A, C</figureCitation>
). Apical system monocyclic, with plating often reduced and genital pores surrounded by number of small platelets (
<figureCitation box="[333,424,1206,1231]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1087,1109]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 4. Morphological characters of Phormosoma placenta (EqMN2341). (A) Aboral view. (B) Detail of apical system; (C) Oral view; (D) Peristome; (E) Ambulacral plates; (F) Interambulacral plates; (G) Valve of tridentate pedicellariae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612572/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
). Periproct large (
<figureCitation box="[632,759,1206,1231]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1087,1109]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 4. Morphological characters of Phormosoma placenta (EqMN2341). (A) Aboral view. (B) Detail of apical system; (C) Oral view; (D) Peristome; (E) Ambulacral plates; (F) Interambulacral plates; (G) Valve of tridentate pedicellariae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612572/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 4A, B</figureCitation>
). Interambulacra about two-thirds wider than ambulacra at ambitus (
<figureCitation box="[257,351,1242,1267]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1087,1109]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 4. Morphological characters of Phormosoma placenta (EqMN2341). (A) Aboral view. (B) Detail of apical system; (C) Oral view; (D) Peristome; (E) Ambulacral plates; (F) Interambulacral plates; (G) Valve of tridentate pedicellariae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612572/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
). Primary spines long, thin, straight, and hollow. Aboral surface with some fleshy spines (live specimens). Secondary spines thin and elongate (like needles). Spines from oral surface similar to those from aboral surface, but shorter and with rounded tips. Ambulacral plate trigeminate, with large central element bearing one or two primary tubercles and pair of ambulacral pores, and two demiplates housing one pore-pair each (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1087,1109]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 4. Morphological characters of Phormosoma placenta (EqMN2341). (A) Aboral view. (B) Detail of apical system; (C) Oral view; (D) Peristome; (E) Ambulacral plates; (F) Interambulacral plates; (G) Valve of tridentate pedicellariae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612572/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 4E</figureCitation>
). Interambulacral plates wide, with one to three primary tubercles forming subequal rows (
<figureCitation box="[1236,1324,1386,1411]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1087,1109]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 4. Morphological characters of Phormosoma placenta (EqMN2341). (A) Aboral view. (B) Detail of apical system; (C) Oral view; (D) Peristome; (E) Ambulacral plates; (F) Interambulacral plates; (G) Valve of tridentate pedicellariae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612572/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 4F</figureCitation>
). Primary tubercles perforated and non-crenulate (
<figureCitation box="[623,752,1422,1447]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1087,1109]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 4. Morphological characters of Phormosoma placenta (EqMN2341). (A) Aboral view. (B) Detail of apical system; (C) Oral view; (D) Peristome; (E) Ambulacral plates; (F) Interambulacral plates; (G) Valve of tridentate pedicellariae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612572/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 4E, F</figureCitation>
). Aboral tubercles irregularly arranged. Oral surface flat, covered by numerous and large tubercles with sunken areoles (
<figureCitation box="[899,993,1458,1483]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1087,1109]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 4. Morphological characters of Phormosoma placenta (EqMN2341). (A) Aboral view. (B) Detail of apical system; (C) Oral view; (D) Peristome; (E) Ambulacral plates; (F) Interambulacral plates; (G) Valve of tridentate pedicellariae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612572/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
). Peristome large, nearly circular and densely covered by overlapped plates (
<figureCitation box="[586,675,1494,1519]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1087,1109]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 4. Morphological characters of Phormosoma placenta (EqMN2341). (A) Aboral view. (B) Detail of apical system; (C) Oral view; (D) Peristome; (E) Ambulacral plates; (F) Interambulacral plates; (G) Valve of tridentate pedicellariae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612572/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1098,2023]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,360,1530,1555]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Pedicellariae.</emphasis>
Only tridentate (
<figureCitation box="[559,650,1530,1555]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="16.[151,250,1087,1109]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetId="figure@16.[151,1436,193,1060]" captionTargetPageId="16" captionText="FIGURE 4. Morphological characters of Phormosoma placenta (EqMN2341). (A) Aboral view. (B) Detail of apical system; (C) Oral view; (D) Peristome; (E) Ambulacral plates; (F) Interambulacral plates; (G) Valve of tridentate pedicellariae." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2612572/files/figure.png" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Fig. 4G</figureCitation>
) and ophicephalous pedicellariae are found in 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1872" box="[1194,1320,1530,1555]" class="Echinoidea" family="Phormosomatidae" genus="Phormosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinothurioida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="placenta">
<emphasis box="[1194,1320,1530,1555]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. placenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. The first 
<typeStatus box="[151,199,1567,1591]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">type</typeStatus>
occurs in smaller numbers than the second 
<typeStatus box="[683,735,1567,1591]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">type</typeStatus>
. Both are very numerous and distributed irregularly over entire test, being particularly abundant on the oral surface towards the edge of the peristome.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1098,2023]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,288,1638,1663]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Colour.</emphasis>
In living specimens, the aboral surface is gray with purple spots and oral surface purplish (
<bibRefCitation author="Bell, F. J." box="[1316,1432,1638,1663]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refId="ref47622" refString="Bell, F. J. (1892) Catalogue of the British Echinoderms in the British Museum (Natural History). Printed by Order of the Trustees, London, 202 pp. Available from: http: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 43772  page / 9 / mode / 1 up (accessed 31 March 2017)" type="book" year="1892">Bell 1892</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen, T. H." box="[151,342,1675,1699]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" refId="ref61217" refString="Mortensen, T. H. (1977) Handbook of the Echinoderms of the Brithish Isles. 2 nd Edition. W. Backhuys, Rotterdam,, 471 pp." type="book" year="1977">Mortensen 1977</bibRefCitation>
). The tube feet are purple, and the spines are nearly colourless (
<bibRefCitation author="Thomson, C. W." box="[1111,1291,1674,1699]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="719 - 756" refId="ref65013" refString="Thomson, C. W. (1874) On the Echinoidea of the ' Porcupine' deep-sea dredging expeditions. Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society, 164, 719 - 756. https: // doi. org / 10.1098 / rstl. 1874.0021" type="journal article" year="1874">Thomson 1874</bibRefCitation>
). Specimens become brownish-yellowish in alcohol (
