<subSubSection lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="11.[151,1437,1098,2023]" lastBlockId="12.[151,1437,151,968]" lastPageId="12" lastPageNumber="13" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1926,1951]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Remarks.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1872" box="[323,472,1926,1951]" class="Echinoidea" family="Phormosomatidae" genus="Phormosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinothurioida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[323,472,1926,1951]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Phormosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
contains four species, of which only 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1872" box="[899,1023,1926,1951]" class="Echinoidea" family="Phormosomatidae" genus="Phormosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinothurioida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="placenta">
<emphasis box="[899,1023,1926,1951]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. placenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
occurs in the Atlantic Ocean. Three subspecies are recognized for 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1872" box="[486,606,1962,1987]" class="Echinoidea" family="Phormosomatidae" genus="Phormosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinothurioida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="placenta">
<emphasis box="[486,606,1962,1987]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. placenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
: 
<taxonomicName authority="placenta Thomson, 1872 a" authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1872" box="[623,1050,1962,1987]" class="Echinoidea" family="Phormosomatidae" genus="Phormosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinothurioida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="subSpecies" species="placenta" subSpecies="placenta">
<emphasis box="[623,849,1962,1987]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. placenta placenta</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Thomson, C. W." box="[856,1050,1962,1987]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="491 - 497" refId="ref64947" refString="Thomson, C. W. (1872) On the Echinoidea of the ' Porcupine' deep-sea dredging expeditions. Proceedings of the Royal Society of London, 1872, 491 - 497. Available from: https: // archive. org / stream / philtrans 00795337 / 00795337  page / n 0 / mode / 2 up (accessed 5 May 2011)" type="journal article" year="1872">Thomson, 1872 a</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
typical form in the North and East Atlantic, 
<taxonomicName authority="A. Agassiz, 1880" authorityName="A. Agassiz" authorityYear="1880" box="[257,674,1998,2023]" class="Echinoidea" family="Phormosomatidae" genus="Phormosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinothurioida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="subSpecies" species="placenta" subSpecies="sigsbei">
<emphasis box="[257,468,1998,2023]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. placenta sigsbei</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Agassiz, A." box="[477,674,1998,2023]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="69 - 84" refId="ref46172" refString="Agassiz, A. (1880) Reports on the results of dredging, under the supervision of Alexander Agassiz, in the Caribbean Sea in 1878 - 79, and along the Atlantic Coast of the United States during summer of 1880, by the U. S. Coast Survey Steamer &quot; Blake &quot;. IX. Preliminary report on the Echini. Bulletin of the Museum of Comparative Zoology at Harvard College, 8, 69 - 84. Available from: http: // www. biodiversitylibrary. org / item / 95375  page / 81 / mode / 1 up (accessed 31 July 2017)" type="journal article" year="1880">
A. Agassiz, 
<quantity box="[618,674,1999,2023]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.7752" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="in" value="1880.0">1880</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in the West Atlantic, and 
<taxonomicName authority="Mortensen, 1934" authorityName="Mortensen" authorityYear="1934" box="[976,1405,1998,2023]" class="Echinoidea" family="Phormosomatidae" genus="Phormosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinothurioida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="subSpecies" species="placenta" subSpecies="africana">
<emphasis box="[976,1205,1998,2023]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">P. placenta africana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Mortensen, T." box="[1214,1405,1999,2023]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" pagination="161 - 167" refId="ref60891" refString="Mortensen, T. (1934) New Echinoidea. Preliminary Notice. Videnskabelige Meddelelser fra Dansk naturhistorisk Forening i KObenhavn, 98, 161 - 167." type="journal article" year="1934">
Mortensen, 
<quantity box="[1349,1405,1999,2023]" metricMagnitude="1" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.91236" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" unit="in" value="1934.0">1934</quantity>
</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
in 
<collectingCountry box="[151,298,151,176]" name="South Africa" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">South Africa</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Mironov, A. N." box="[314,484,151,176]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="120 - 129" refId="ref59922" refString="Mironov, A. N. (2014) Deep-sea fauna of European seas: An annotated species check-list of benthic invertebrates living deeper than 2000 m in the seas bordering Europe. Echinoidea. Invertebrate Zoology, 11 (1), 120 - 129. https: // doi. org / 10.15298 / invertzool. 11.1.12" type="journal article" year="2014">Mironov 2014</bibRefCitation>
). These subspecies are distinguished mainly on the basis of the number of coronal plates and in the size and disposition of the tubercles on aboral surface. 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomson, C. W." box="[970,1159,188,213]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="491 - 497" refId="ref64947" refString="Thomson, C. W. (1872) On the Echinoidea of the ' Porcupine' deep-sea dredging expeditions. Proceedings of the Royal Society of London, 1872, 491 - 497. Available from: https: // archive. org / stream / philtrans 00795337 / 00795337  page / n 0 / mode / 2 up (accessed 5 May 2011)" type="journal article" year="1872">Thomson (1872)</bibRefCitation>
published an abstract in which he established the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1872" box="[531,680,223,248]" class="Echinoidea" family="Phormosomatidae" genus="Phormosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinothurioida" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[531,680,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Phormosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and the species 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1872" box="[885,1014,223,248]" class="Echinoidea" family="Phormosomatidae" genus="Phormosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinothurioida" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="placenta">
<emphasis box="[885,1014,223,248]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">P. placenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. However, in this work, the author provided only a short description of the genus and the locality of the material used to designate the species. 
<bibRefCitation author="Thomson, C. W." box="[151,339,295,320]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="719 - 756" refId="ref65013" refString="Thomson, C. W. (1874) On the Echinoidea of the ' Porcupine' deep-sea dredging expeditions. Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society, 164, 719 - 756. https: // doi. org / 10.1098 / rstl. 1874.0021" type="journal article" year="1874">Thomson (1874)</bibRefCitation>
presented a detailed description and provided several illustrations of the taxonomic characters of the species. One of the most conspicuous characters in live specimens of 
<emphasis box="[1004,1143,332,357]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Phomosoma</emphasis>
is the presence of aboral fleshy spines, which may partially or totally obscure the dorsal surface of the test or form a “fence” along the periphery of the urchin. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Emson, R. H. &amp; Young, C. M." box="[577,848,404,429]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="101 - 111" refId="ref52532" refString="Emson, R. H. &amp; Young, C. M. (1998) Form and function of the primary spines of two bathyal echinothuriid sea urchins. Acta Zoologica, Stockholm, 79 (2), 101 - 111. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1463 - 6395.1998. tb 01149. x" type="journal article" year="1998">Emson &amp; Young (1998)</bibRefCitation>
, virtually all the primary spines of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1872" box="[1242,1366,404,429]" class="Echinoidea" family="Phormosomatidae" genus="Phormosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinothurioida" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="placenta">
<emphasis box="[1242,1366,404,429]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">P. placenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are to some extent fleshy, as all the oral and lateral spines have a small fleshy enlargement near the tip and the blunt oral walking spines are enlarged by a thick fleshy covering. The main function of these spines most probably is defence (
<bibRefCitation author="Emson, R. H. &amp; Young, C. M." box="[158,415,512,536]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="101 - 111" refId="ref52532" refString="Emson, R. H. &amp; Young, C. M. (1998) Form and function of the primary spines of two bathyal echinothuriid sea urchins. Acta Zoologica, Stockholm, 79 (2), 101 - 111. https: // doi. org / 10.1111 / j. 1463 - 6395.1998. tb 01149. x" type="journal article" year="1998">Emson &amp; Young 1998</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="12.[151,1437,151,968]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,400,548,573]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Ecological notes.</emphasis>
Individuals of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1872" box="[577,702,548,573]" class="Echinoidea" family="Phormosomatidae" genus="Phormosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinothurioida" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="placenta">
<emphasis box="[577,702,548,573]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">P. placenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
seem to aggregate and this pattern was attributed to their slowmoving deposit-feeding mode of life (
<bibRefCitation author="Grassle, F. J. &amp; Sanders, H. L. &amp; Hessler, R. R. &amp; Rowe, G. T. &amp; McLellan, T." box="[590,814,583,608]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="457 - 481" refId="ref54391" refString="Grassle, F. J., Sanders, H. L., Hessler, R. R., Rowe, G. T. &amp; McLellan, T. (1975) Pattern and zonation: a study of the bathyal megafauna using the research submersible Alvin. Deep-Sea Research, 22, 457 - 481. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / 0011 - 7471 (75) 90020 - 0" type="journal article" year="1975">
Grassle 
<emphasis box="[685,745,583,608]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">et al.</emphasis>
1975
</bibRefCitation>
). 
<bibRefCitation author="Pawson, D. L." box="[836,1008,584,608]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="129 - 145" refId="ref61601" refString="Pawson, D. L. (1982) Papers from the Echinoderm Conference. 8. Deep-sea echinoderms in the Tongue of the Ocean, Bahamas Islands: a survey, using the research submersible Alvin. Australian Museum Memoir, 16, 129 - 145. https: // doi. org / 10.3853 / j. 0067 - 1967.16.1982.362" type="journal article" year="1982">Pawson (1982)</bibRefCitation>
found only mucus-consolidated mud balls in the guts of this species. 
<bibRefCitation author="Tyler, P. A. &amp; Gage, J. D." box="[515,754,620,645]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="63 - 74" refId="ref66063" refString="Tyler, P. A. &amp; Gage, J. D. (1984) The reproductive biology of echinothuriid and cidarid sea urchins from the deep sea (Rockall Trough, North-East Atlantic Ocean). Marine Biology, 80 (1), 63 - 74. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / BF 00393129" type="journal article" year="1984">Tyler &amp; Gage (1984)</bibRefCitation>
believe that the species must have a relatively rapid growth rate (up to a TD of 
<quantity box="[387,544,655,680]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.25" metricValueMax="4.5" metricValueMin="4.0" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="42.5" valueMax="45.0" valueMin="40.0">40 to 45 mm</quantity>
). At this point, gonad development begins and there is a slowing of somatic growth, resulting in an accumulation of adults in the 
<quantity box="[763,912,692,717]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="6.5" metricValueMax="7.5" metricValueMin="5.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="65.0" valueMax="75.0" valueMin="55.0">55 to 75 mm</quantity>
TD range. Above 
<quantity box="[1130,1211,692,717]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="7.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="75.0">75 mm</quantity>
TD, the population numbers decline, and generally few individuals larger than 
<quantity box="[830,910,727,752]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="8.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="85.0">85 mm</quantity>
TD are found. 
<bibRefCitation author="Tyler, P. A. &amp; Gage, J. D." box="[1089,1329,727,752]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="63 - 74" refId="ref66063" refString="Tyler, P. A. &amp; Gage, J. D. (1984) The reproductive biology of echinothuriid and cidarid sea urchins from the deep sea (Rockall Trough, North-East Atlantic Ocean). Marine Biology, 80 (1), 63 - 74. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / BF 00393129" type="journal article" year="1984">Tyler &amp; Gage (1984)</bibRefCitation>
recorded specimens with 
<quantity box="[331,410,764,789]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="4.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="45.0">45 mm</quantity>
TD possessing developing gonads, while specimens between 47 and 
<quantity box="[1187,1265,764,789]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="5.5" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" unit="mm" value="55.0">55 mm</quantity>
TD showed no evidence of reproductive development. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Pearse, J. S." box="[749,906,799,824]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="110 - 116" refId="ref61760" refString="Pearse, J. S. (1969) Slow developing demersal embryos and larvae of the Antarctic sea star Odontaster validus. Marine Biology, 3 (2), 110 - 116. https: // doi. org / 10.1007 / BF 00353429" type="journal article" year="1969">Pearse (1969)</bibRefCitation>
, the lecithotrophic larvae of 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1872" box="[1228,1351,799,824]" class="Echinoidea" family="Phormosomatidae" genus="Phormosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinothurioida" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="placenta">
<emphasis box="[1228,1351,799,824]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">P. placenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are not demersal and develop at or close to the surface. 
<bibRefCitation author="Young, C. M. &amp; Cameron, J. L." box="[697,993,836,861]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="1629 - 1639" refId="ref67681" refString="Young, C. M. &amp; Cameron, J. L. (1987) Laboratory and in situ flotation rates of lecithotrophic eggs from the bathyal echinoid Phormosoma placenta. Deep Sea Research Part A. Oceanographic Research Papers, 34 (9), 1629 - 1639. https: // doi. org / 10.1016 / 0198 - 0149 (87) 90112 - 9" type="journal article" year="1987">Young &amp; Cameron (1987)</bibRefCitation>
conducted a study on flotation rates of lecithotrophic eggs from 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Thomson" authorityYear="1872" box="[442,569,871,896]" class="Echinoidea" family="Phormosomatidae" genus="Phormosoma" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Echinothurioida" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Echinodermata" rank="species" species="placenta">
<emphasis box="[442,569,871,896]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">P. placenta</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and pointed out the enhanced physiological tolerance in embryos of deepwater echinothuriids relative to larvae of shelf and coastal echinoderms. According to 
<bibRefCitation author="Benavides-Serrato, M. &amp; Borrero-Perez, G. H." pageId="12" pageNumber="13" pagination="1 - 458" refId="ref47763" refString="Benavides-Serrato, M. &amp; Borrero-Perez, G. H. (2010) Equinodermos de la plataforma y la franja superior del talud continental del Caribe colombiano. In: INVEMAR (Ed.), Biodiversidad del margen continental del Caribe colombiano, Serie de Publicaciones Especiales, Invemar, 20, pp. 1 - 458." type="journal article" year="2010">Benavides-Serrato &amp; Borrero-Pérez (2010)</bibRefCitation>
, this species is abundant in the Colombian part of the Caribbean.
</paragraph>
